#: resources/locales/en/methodology.md:1
msgid "CO₂-Budget calculation"
msgstr ""

#: resources/locales/en/methodology.md:3
msgid ""
"A so-called CO₂ budget refers to the amount of CO₂ that may be emitted in "
"order to limit global warming to a specific temperature (e.g. 1.5 °C). As "
"such, these budgets form the basis for meeting the goals set by the Paris "
"Agreement. The Paris Agreement was adopted at the end of 2015 during the UN "
"Climate Conference in Paris. In this agreement, nations commit to limiting "
"global warming to \"well below\" 2 °C compared to pre-industrial levels and "
"to making efforts to limit it to 1.5 °C. This means that every country and "
"its population is assigned responsibility for addressing their share of the "
"global problem. This is quantified through CO₂ budgets."
msgstr ""

#: resources/locales/en/methodology.md:13
msgid ""
"This tool shows the remaining CO₂ budget that the selected city may still "
"emit in order to make its fair contribution to limiting global warming to a "
"specific temperature (1.5 °C, 1.7 °C, or 2 °C). To determine this, we first "
"calculate the global CO₂ budget available to us to limit warming to the "
"temperatures mentioned above. As the Paris Climate Agreement was adopted at "
"the end of 2015, we refer to the CO₂ budget from 2016 onwards. However, we "
"use figures for the global CO₂ budget from the [2021 IPCC report (Table "
"SPM.2, p. 29)]{1}. This report specifies the global budget from 2020 "
"onwards. To still calculate the budget from 2016 onwards, we add the global "
"CO₂ emissions between 2016 and 2020 to the global budget of 2020. The global "
"CO₂ budget for the various temperature limits is then scaled down to the "
"selected city's share of the world population. This urban budget encompasses "
"all CO₂ emissions caused by the local population."
msgstr ""

#: resources/locales/en/methodology.md:27
msgid ""
"We compare the scaled-down budget with the actually measured emissions. The "
"cities for which the CO₂ budget tool is available measure their emissions "
"according to the [BISKO methodology]{1}. The CO₂ accounting for Heidelberg "
"until 2018 shows that the so-called BISKO emissions cover only around 64 % "
"of the total emissions caused by the Heidelberg's population. The reason for "
"this incomplete coverage is that, put simply, the BISKO standard only takes "
"into account emissions generated within the city limits, but not those "
"caused by the city's population outside those boundaries. As we use the "
"emission values determined by the cities according to the BISKO methodology, "
"we must also take a nuanced view of the CO₂ budget for the selected city . A "
"part of the budget, in the case of Heidelberg precisely 64 %, can be "
"allocated to BISKO emissions. The remainder is reserved for non-BISKO "
"emissions. According to this reasoning, and assuming that the share of BISKO "
"emissions in total emissions is similar across all available cities, the "
"final CO₂ budget represents only 64 % of the total budget of the local urban "
"population."
msgstr ""

